1
00:03:03,810 --> 00:03:06,520
Snuggle in, sweetie! It's cold out there.

2
00:03:11,400 --> 00:03:14,740
Why is it snowing, Grandma?
Where does it come from?

3
00:03:15,330 --> 00:03:17,730
Oh, that's a long story, sweetheart.

4
00:03:18,700 --> 00:03:21,910
- I wanna hear.
- Oh, not tonight. Go to sleep.

5
00:03:22,620 --> 00:03:25,910
I'm not sleepy. Tell me, please.

6
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:28,080
Well, all right.

7
00:03:29,590 --> 00:03:31,670
Let's see...

8
00:03:32,220 --> 00:03:36,000
I guess it would have to start with... scissors!

9
00:03:36,100 --> 00:03:38,170
Scissors?

10
00:03:38,260 --> 00:03:41,930
Well, there are all kinds of scissors.

11
00:03:42,980 --> 00:03:47,810
And once there was even a man
who had scissors for hands.

12
00:03:47,900 --> 00:03:49,860
- A man?
- Yes.

13
00:03:49,940 --> 00:03:53,690
- Hands scissors?
- No, scissor hands.

14
00:03:54,950 --> 00:03:59,530
You know the mansion
on top of the mountain?

15
00:04:00,080 --> 00:04:01,740
It's haunted.

16
00:04:01,830 --> 00:04:03,910
Well...

17
00:04:04,540 --> 00:04:06,620
A long time ago...

18
00:04:08,130 --> 00:04:10,800
...an inventor lived in that mansion.

19
00:04:12,340 --> 00:04:15,090
He made many things, I suppose.

20
00:04:21,140 --> 00:04:23,220
<i>He also created a man.</i>

21
00:04:24,940 --> 00:04:30,890
<i>He gave him insides,</i>
<i>a heart, a brain, everything.</i>

22
00:04:32,070 --> 00:04:34,140
<i>Well, almost everything.</i>

23
00:04:36,570 --> 00:04:40,440
<i>You see, the inventor was very old.</i>

24
00:04:40,540 --> 00:04:44,030
<i>He died before he got to finish</i>
<i>the man he invented.</i>

25
00:04:45,500 --> 00:04:48,290
<i>So the man was left by himself...</i>

26
00:04:49,040 --> 00:04:52,460
<i>... incomplete and all alone.</i>

27
00:04:54,090 --> 00:04:56,170
<i>He didn't have a name?</i>

28
00:04:56,880 --> 00:04:58,960
<i>Of course he had a name.</i>

29
00:04:59,760 --> 00:05:01,840
<i>His name was Edward.</i>

30
00:05:48,390 --> 00:05:50,270
Avon calling!

31
00:05:50,360 --> 00:05:53,690
- Weren't you just here?
- No, not since last season!

32
00:05:54,230 --> 00:05:59,190
Today I've come to show you our exquisite
new line of softer colours, in shadows...

33
00:05:59,280 --> 00:06:01,020
...blushes and lipstick.

34
00:06:01,120 --> 00:06:04,820
Everything you need to accent and highlight
your changing look.

35
00:06:04,910 --> 00:06:08,240
My changing look... That's good!

36
00:06:08,330 --> 00:06:11,830
I also have a complete selection
of your old favourites...

37
00:06:11,920 --> 00:06:16,330
...those tried and true products we've all
come to depend on year in and year out.

38
00:06:16,420 --> 00:06:19,000
Come on, Peg,
I never buy anything from you.

39
00:06:19,090 --> 00:06:21,220
I know. Bye, Helen.

40
00:06:21,890 --> 00:06:26,470
Um, you didn't have to call me, ma'am.
You could have taken care of this by yourself.

41
00:06:26,560 --> 00:06:28,630
I could? I don't think so.

42
00:06:28,730 --> 00:06:31,510
It's easy. Your food trap's clogged, that's all.

43
00:06:31,600 --> 00:06:34,060
See this bolt here? You just unscrew this...

44
00:06:34,150 --> 00:06:35,770
Mm-hm...

45
00:06:35,860 --> 00:06:37,600
And out she pops.

46
00:06:37,690 --> 00:06:40,230
On TV they say you repairmen
are a lonely bunch.

47
00:06:40,320 --> 00:06:45,070
Housewives get lonely too, though you may
not realise it since they haven't made an ad.

48
00:06:45,160 --> 00:06:51,080
And then you just take this and put it back in
here nice and easy. Be careful not to force it.

49
00:06:51,170 --> 00:06:53,410
And then you just screw this back on.

50
00:06:53,500 --> 00:06:56,460
Oh, now who could that be?

51
00:06:57,260 --> 00:06:59,330
Will you excuse me for a moment?

52
00:07:00,050 --> 00:07:04,180
Now, don't go anywhere. I'll be right back.
This is fascinatin'!

53
00:07:04,260 --> 00:07:06,670
I wouldn't wanna miss a moment of it!

54
00:07:11,350 --> 00:07:14,560
- Good morning, Joyce. Avon calling!
- Why, Peg...

55
00:07:14,650 --> 00:07:17,850
Have you gone blind?
Can't you see that vehicle in my drive?

56
00:07:20,150 --> 00:07:21,610
Oh. Yes.

57
00:07:21,700 --> 00:07:24,190
Don't you realise that means I'm busy?

58
00:07:25,950 --> 00:07:28,490
OK, now we should decide on lipsticks.

59
00:07:28,580 --> 00:07:33,240
OK, dear, did you like the Winsome Wahini,
which looked charming on you...

60
00:07:33,330 --> 00:07:35,740
...or the Bahimini Bliss?

61
00:07:35,840 --> 00:07:37,910
- I like 'em both.
- Well, great!

62
00:07:39,010 --> 00:07:42,170
You don't actually think
I have any money, do you?

63
00:07:54,440 --> 00:07:57,850
Ding-dong! The Avon lady!

64
00:08:00,900 --> 00:08:02,780
Just not my day.

65
00:09:59,650 --> 00:10:01,720
Oh, my goodness!

66
00:10:20,920 --> 00:10:23,410
Oh, it's so beautiful!

67
00:10:45,230 --> 00:10:47,310
Hello?

68
00:11:14,140 --> 00:11:16,210
Hello?

69
00:11:23,770 --> 00:11:26,520
Hello? Avon calling!

70
00:12:01,770 --> 00:12:03,840
Oh, my!

71
00:12:06,400 --> 00:12:08,470
Hello?

72
00:12:09,400 --> 00:12:11,480
Hello?

73
00:12:13,030 --> 00:12:18,490
I'm Peg Boggs.
I'm your local Avon representative. Hello?

74
00:12:29,300 --> 00:12:34,340
I... I'm sorry to barge in like this,
but you don't have any reason to be afraid.

75
00:12:35,010 --> 00:12:38,130
Ooh! This is some huge house, isn't it?

76
00:12:38,220 --> 00:12:41,970
Thank goodness
for those aerobics... classes.

77
00:13:36,900 --> 00:13:39,400
Hello? Hello?

78
00:13:40,450 --> 00:13:42,780
Why are you hiding back there?

79
00:13:46,250 --> 00:13:49,500
You don't have to hide from me.
I'm Peg Boggs.

80
00:13:49,580 --> 00:13:51,990
I'm your local Avon representative...

81
00:13:52,090 --> 00:13:55,170
...and I'm as harmless as cherry pie...

82
00:13:55,260 --> 00:13:56,590
Oh, my!

83
00:13:56,670 --> 00:13:59,210
I can see that I've disturbed you.

84
00:13:59,300 --> 00:14:01,510
How stupid of me. I'll just be going now.

85
00:14:01,600 --> 00:14:03,670
Don't go.

86
00:14:09,980 --> 00:14:12,060
Oh, my!

87
00:14:13,020 --> 00:14:15,060
What happened to you?

88
00:14:15,150 --> 00:14:17,190
- I'm not finished.
- Ohh!

89
00:14:17,280 --> 00:14:19,900
Put those down.
Don't come any closer. Please...

90
00:14:27,660 --> 00:14:29,740
Those are your hands?

91
00:14:30,630 --> 00:14:33,080
Those are your hands!

92
00:14:37,130 --> 00:14:39,210
What happened to you?

93
00:14:41,680 --> 00:14:43,750
Where are your parents? Um...

94
00:14:44,680 --> 00:14:46,760
Your mother?

95
00:14:47,810 --> 00:14:50,100
Your father?

96
00:14:50,730 --> 00:14:52,390
He didn't wake up.

97
00:14:56,990 --> 00:15:00,900
Are you alone?
Do you live up here all by yourself?

98
00:15:05,080 --> 00:15:07,150
What happened to your face?

99
00:15:10,830 --> 00:15:13,290
I won't hurt you.

100
00:15:14,500 --> 00:15:18,120
At the very least,
let me give you a good astringent.

101
00:15:18,210 --> 00:15:20,620
This will help to prevent infection.

102
00:15:32,100 --> 00:15:34,180
What's your name?

103
00:15:34,520 --> 00:15:36,600
Edward.

104
00:15:36,940 --> 00:15:39,020
Edward...

105
00:15:42,070 --> 00:15:44,690
I think you should just come home with me.

106
00:15:58,090 --> 00:15:59,630
Ohh!

107
00:15:59,710 --> 00:16:02,120
- I'm... I'm sorry.
- No. No, don't be.

108
00:16:02,680 --> 00:16:06,510
You go ahead and look.
You have every reason to be excited.

109
00:16:10,520 --> 00:16:12,590
Oh! You OK?

110
00:16:13,480 --> 00:16:15,190
You OK?

111
00:16:45,640 --> 00:16:46,830
Hello?

112
00:16:46,930 --> 00:16:48,550
Hi. Yeah, it's Marge.

113
00:16:48,640 --> 00:16:53,550
I was standing outside talking to Carol, and
Peg drove by. She had somebody with her.

114
00:16:53,640 --> 00:16:56,400
- Did you get a good look at him?
- No, I didn't.

115
00:16:56,480 --> 00:16:59,100
Did she say anything to you
about having a guest?

116
00:16:59,190 --> 00:17:02,520
Nothing at all.
She rang my doorbell at the crack of dawn.

117
00:17:02,610 --> 00:17:05,560
No... OK, I'll meet you on the corner.

118
00:17:05,660 --> 00:17:07,730
Right. Bye.

119
00:17:11,540 --> 00:17:13,530
Oh! Damn!

120
00:17:26,300 --> 00:17:28,420
Here we go, dear. This is our house.

121
00:17:28,510 --> 00:17:32,130
You can just go right in
and make yourself right at home, OK?

122
00:17:32,220 --> 00:17:35,560
We'll have something to eat or drink, or...
Whatever you...

123
00:17:35,640 --> 00:17:40,520
Here, dear. Here we go. This is the front door.
Here we go. Right in here.

124
00:17:40,610 --> 00:17:44,900
Joyce? I just saw this strange guy
drive in with Peg. I didn't get a good look.

125
00:17:44,990 --> 00:17:46,810
He looked kinda pale.

126
00:17:46,900 --> 00:17:49,190
On my way. Don't do anything without me.

127
00:17:49,280 --> 00:17:51,360
Yes! Be right there!

128
00:17:57,250 --> 00:17:59,320
Here we are.

129
00:18:17,810 --> 00:18:22,020
So... um, this is the living room
and back here are the bedrooms.

130
00:18:22,610 --> 00:18:25,150
You want to see the pictures? All right.

131
00:18:26,280 --> 00:18:30,690
Well, this is my husband Bill.
He's a bowling champion.

132
00:18:30,780 --> 00:18:33,110
Do you know what bowling is?

133
00:18:33,200 --> 00:18:35,030
Bowling?

134
00:18:35,120 --> 00:18:38,040
No. Well... Here they are
down at the lake, fishing.

135
00:18:38,120 --> 00:18:43,250
I think Kevin looks a little glum
because they didn't catch anything that day.

136
00:18:44,130 --> 00:18:47,790
And, um... here's my daughter Kim.

137
00:18:48,420 --> 00:18:50,500
All dressed for the junior prom.

138
00:18:58,850 --> 00:19:01,470
She's a senior now, if you can believe it!

139
00:19:02,230 --> 00:19:05,100
She's camping in the mountains
with friends...

140
00:19:05,190 --> 00:19:08,110
...but she'll be back in a few days.
You can meet then.

141
00:19:17,540 --> 00:19:19,610
Isn't she beautiful?

142
00:19:27,460 --> 00:19:29,540
That's my family.

143
00:19:30,380 --> 00:19:33,140
Come along.
I'll show you the rest of the house.

144
00:19:33,220 --> 00:19:36,050
Then you can just freshen up
and make yourself at home.

145
00:19:36,140 --> 00:19:40,050
That's the kitchen over there.
Help yourself to anything you want.

146
00:19:40,140 --> 00:19:43,640
Those are grapes.
And, um... back here are the bedrooms.

147
00:19:43,730 --> 00:19:47,600
Let me get you some towels
and I'll see what we can find for you to wear.

148
00:19:47,690 --> 00:19:52,820
You know what? I think I have some of
Bill's old clothes in here. This is perfect!

149
00:19:53,740 --> 00:19:55,820
Here. These should just fit you.

150
00:19:55,910 --> 00:19:59,530
Oh! Don't be alarmed. That's just the phone.

151
00:19:59,620 --> 00:20:04,080
Now you can go in Kim's room
and put these on, and I'll be right with you.

152
00:21:49,690 --> 00:21:52,940
No, no, scissors. No, scissors.

153
00:21:53,030 --> 00:21:57,110
That's right. Well, he was...
born up there or... something.

154
00:21:57,200 --> 00:22:01,190
- <i>Have you seen him before?</i>
- No, I doubt he's ever been off the grounds.

155
00:22:01,280 --> 00:22:04,070
<i>Then how did you ever get together with him?</i>

156
00:22:04,160 --> 00:22:08,290
Listen, I have to go now.
I'll talk to you later, Marge. Bye-bye.

157
00:22:18,300 --> 00:22:20,380
Sorry, Edward, I didn't...

158
00:22:21,390 --> 00:22:23,300
May I help you with this?

159
00:22:23,390 --> 00:22:25,470
Thank you.

160
00:22:28,140 --> 00:22:31,150
There you go. Oh dear, you've cut your face.

161
00:22:31,230 --> 00:22:33,770
Here. Let me just get this right off.

162
00:22:33,860 --> 00:22:35,850
- Does that hurt?
- No.

163
00:22:35,940 --> 00:22:38,350
Good. OK. Now, let's get you dressed.

164
00:22:39,610 --> 00:22:41,690
OK...

165
00:22:42,240 --> 00:22:45,360
There we go. Very fine!

166
00:22:49,920 --> 00:22:51,990
You look fine, just fine!

167
00:22:57,220 --> 00:22:59,920
Helen, come on! She wouldn't wait for you.

168
00:23:00,840 --> 00:23:02,920
I've got rollers in my damn hair!

169
00:23:21,530 --> 00:23:23,070
OK...

170
00:23:23,160 --> 00:23:26,240
Now, what did I do with my sciss?

171
00:23:27,290 --> 00:23:29,780
Edward, um... would you?

172
00:23:31,460 --> 00:23:33,080
Thank you.

173
00:23:33,710 --> 00:23:37,240
You know, I have a doctor friend
who I think could help you.

174
00:23:37,760 --> 00:23:39,830
- Really?
- Yes.

175
00:23:40,800 --> 00:23:42,880
Now, I can help with the scars...

176
00:23:45,970 --> 00:23:50,550
But I just wanna consult the big
Avon handbook before doing anything.

177
00:24:35,020 --> 00:24:37,100
Kevin!

178
00:24:39,860 --> 00:24:41,350
Kevin!

179
00:24:41,440 --> 00:24:43,520
It's not polite to stare, dear.

180
00:24:46,280 --> 00:24:50,410
Think how it would make you feel
if somebody were staring at you.

181
00:24:50,540 --> 00:24:54,670
- I wouldn't care.
- Well, I would, so don't do it!

182
00:24:54,750 --> 00:24:58,280
Well, this must be
quite a change for you, right, Ed?

183
00:24:58,380 --> 00:25:01,790
- Edward, dear. I think he prefers Edward.
- Oh, sure.

184
00:25:02,550 --> 00:25:07,210
So what have you been doin' with yourself
up there in that big old place? I bet the...

185
00:25:07,300 --> 00:25:11,050
- I bet the view must be spectacular, huh, Ed?
- Edward!

186
00:25:11,720 --> 00:25:12,760
Yes?

187
00:25:14,140 --> 00:25:16,430
No, I... I just...

188
00:25:16,520 --> 00:25:19,360
See all the way to the ocean, I bet, huh?

189
00:25:19,440 --> 00:25:21,270
Sometimes.

190
00:25:22,860 --> 00:25:25,900
Bill, could I have the salt and pepper, please?

191
00:25:27,570 --> 00:25:31,870
Bill, dear, could I have
the salt and pepper, please? Thank you.

192
00:25:32,080 --> 00:25:34,150
Kevin!

193
00:25:45,760 --> 00:25:47,830
Kevin!

194
00:25:50,470 --> 00:25:52,550
Man, those things are cool!

195
00:25:53,060 --> 00:25:56,590
I bet they're razor-sharp.
One karate chop to a guy's neck...

196
00:25:56,690 --> 00:25:58,150
Kevin!

197
00:26:01,650 --> 00:26:03,110
Edward...

198
00:26:03,610 --> 00:26:06,480
...would you like some butter for your bread?

199
00:26:11,080 --> 00:26:12,740
Great!

200
00:26:13,160 --> 00:26:15,240
Thank you.

201
00:26:17,670 --> 00:26:20,340
Hey, can I bring him to
show and tell on Monday?

202
00:26:20,420 --> 00:26:22,460
Kevin, I've had enough.

203
00:26:27,260 --> 00:26:29,300
Do you think you can sleep?

204
00:26:29,390 --> 00:26:32,800
I know things feel strange,
but soon you'll feel right at home.

205
00:26:33,680 --> 00:26:35,760
- Good night.
- Good night.

206
00:27:37,080 --> 00:27:40,030
The light concealing cream goes on first...

207
00:27:40,540 --> 00:27:42,780
...then you blend and blend and blend.

208
00:27:42,880 --> 00:27:44,830
Blending is the secret.

209
00:27:44,920 --> 00:27:47,000
Mm-hm!

210
00:27:47,710 --> 00:27:49,460
More concealing cream...

211
00:27:49,550 --> 00:27:52,170
Your complexion is so fair!

212
00:27:52,260 --> 00:27:54,800
Now, this has a touch of lavender in it...

213
00:27:55,720 --> 00:27:57,600
Give it a try here.

214
00:27:57,680 --> 00:27:59,970
Close enough!

215
00:28:00,060 --> 00:28:02,550
OK, this should do the trick here.

216
00:28:06,110 --> 00:28:07,350
Hmph!

217
00:28:08,740 --> 00:28:10,810
I have another idea.

218
00:28:11,610 --> 00:28:16,030
We'll cover up the scars
and start with a completely smooth surface.

219
00:28:29,880 --> 00:28:31,960
Darn this stuff!

220
00:28:41,600 --> 00:28:45,520
<i>They still have 11 on the scoreboard,</i>
<i>and it's three to one.</i>

221
00:28:48,020 --> 00:28:49,820
<i>It's through the gap to Warren.</i>

222
00:28:53,950 --> 00:28:55,860
<i>Now they change it to 12 hits.</i>

223
00:28:55,950 --> 00:28:58,110
Turn it up, Kevin, I can't hear it!

224
00:29:00,950 --> 00:29:02,700
Kevin!

225
00:29:04,790 --> 00:29:07,540
- <i>It's hammered!</i>
- Did you hear that, Mr Boggs?

226
00:29:07,630 --> 00:29:10,000
- No, make it louder!
- <i>It's gone...</i>

227
00:29:10,090 --> 00:29:12,160
<i>... it's out of here, it's history!</i>

228
00:29:17,600 --> 00:29:19,140
Dad...

229
00:29:19,220 --> 00:29:20,930
Look!

230
00:29:21,020 --> 00:29:24,300
<i>... to make it a five-run inning</i>
<i>and blow this game to pieces!</i>

231
00:29:24,390 --> 00:29:26,220
I'll be darned.

232
00:29:42,370 --> 00:29:44,200
They filled the whole tape!

233
00:29:44,290 --> 00:29:47,370
<i>What's going on over there, Peg?</i>
<i>Call me.</i>

234
00:29:47,460 --> 00:29:50,580
<i>Hi, it's Marge. Who is he? Call me.</i>

235
00:29:50,670 --> 00:29:55,080
<i>Oh, by the way, I hear it's pouring rain in</i>
<i>the mountains. Do you think the kids are OK?</i>

236
00:29:55,170 --> 00:30:00,050
<i>Hey there, darlin'! The gals are</i>
<i>all in a tizzy about your secret visitor.</i>

237
00:30:00,140 --> 00:30:02,680
<i>You can't keep him a secret for ever!</i>

238
00:30:16,780 --> 00:30:22,020
Well, it's just wonderful, Ed. My God,
you have the whole family in there, don't ya?

239
00:30:22,120 --> 00:30:26,200
<i>And he answers the challenge at first</i>
<i>with a strike of his own.</i>

240
00:30:27,620 --> 00:30:29,700
Edward, come here.

241
00:30:37,630 --> 00:30:39,880
No, no, no, that's a terrible idea, son!

242
00:30:39,970 --> 00:30:43,840
Go to the garage and get the oil can.
We don't want him rusting up on us.

243
00:30:49,850 --> 00:30:51,310
Ohh!

244
00:30:51,400 --> 00:30:53,720
Edward, you did us!

245
00:30:54,400 --> 00:30:56,730
- Oh, Bill, it's us!
- Yes, it is.

246
00:30:56,820 --> 00:30:58,900
Oh, Edward!

247
00:31:00,110 --> 00:31:04,780
It's not heaven he's from,
it's straight from the stinking flames of hell.

248
00:31:04,870 --> 00:31:07,410
The power of Satan is in him, I can feel it.

249
00:31:07,500 --> 00:31:10,950
- Can't you? Have you sheep strayed so far?
- We're not sheep.

250
00:31:11,040 --> 00:31:13,120
Don't come near me.

251
00:31:16,710 --> 00:31:19,830
That's right. Go on, get outta here, run!

252
00:31:19,930 --> 00:31:22,000
Edward, don't you listen to her!

253
00:31:22,390 --> 00:31:26,760
Don't worry about her, Edward.
She's just a little loony, that's all.

254
00:31:32,560 --> 00:31:34,020
Hi!

255
00:31:34,110 --> 00:31:37,020
You-all are hidin' in there like hermit crabs.

256
00:31:37,110 --> 00:31:38,940
Hi, Joyce. Hi!

257
00:31:39,030 --> 00:31:42,110
Shame on you,
keepin' your unusual guest to yourself.

258
00:31:42,200 --> 00:31:44,490
We think that's mighty selfish of you.

259
00:31:44,580 --> 00:31:46,240
Things have been hectic here.

260
00:31:46,330 --> 00:31:49,410
That is so sweet of you
to wanna correct the situation.

261
00:31:49,500 --> 00:31:51,370
What time <i>does</i> the barbecue begin?

262
00:31:51,460 --> 00:31:52,920
Barbecue?

263
00:31:53,000 --> 00:31:55,870
You intend to introduce
your guest to your friends...

264
00:31:55,960 --> 00:31:58,040
...don't you?
- I'll bring coleslaw.

265
00:31:59,970 --> 00:32:02,420
And I will bring the ambrosia salad!

266
00:32:03,390 --> 00:32:06,300
- What time was it that you said?
- Uh, what time...

267
00:32:06,390 --> 00:32:08,470
- Bill!
- About five?

268
00:32:08,560 --> 00:32:09,970
Bill!

269
00:32:10,060 --> 00:32:12,390
He has been sent first to tempt you!

270
00:32:13,150 --> 00:32:18,480
But it's not too late.
You must push him from you, expel him.

271
00:32:18,570 --> 00:32:21,020
Trample down the perversion of nature.

272
00:32:21,570 --> 00:32:24,860
Did you hear that?
He's a perversion of nature.

273
00:32:24,950 --> 00:32:26,940
Why, isn't that excitin'?

274
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:33,070
- Bye-bye.
- Thanks so much.

275
00:32:36,670 --> 00:32:38,750
Bill! Bill?

276
00:32:41,590 --> 00:32:45,420
You really can't have a picnic or a barbecue
without devilled eggs.

277
00:32:45,510 --> 00:32:48,720
They're just... the best. They make a thing.

278
00:32:48,810 --> 00:32:53,600
Oh, Edward, that's wonderful!
I didn't know you'd chopped the whole thing.

279
00:32:53,690 --> 00:32:55,510
We're gonna be...

280
00:32:55,610 --> 00:32:58,010
Oh. All right now, it's just a nick.

281
00:32:58,110 --> 00:33:00,810
There's no need to be nervous, dear.

282
00:33:00,900 --> 00:33:06,410
Esmeralda won't be here. And the rest of
the neighbours, they're really very nice.

283
00:33:06,490 --> 00:33:09,860
There's no need to be nervous.
They're so eager to meet you!

284
00:33:09,950 --> 00:33:11,780
You just have to be yourself.

285
00:33:11,870 --> 00:33:15,490
- Myself?
- That's right. Just your own sweet self.

286
00:35:41,900 --> 00:35:45,480
- Thanks, Edward.
- Hey! Play scissors, paper, stone with us.

287
00:35:45,570 --> 00:35:47,770
Play scissors what?

288
00:35:47,860 --> 00:35:50,730
I got a doctor friend
might be able to help you.

289
00:35:51,610 --> 00:35:55,690
- He did them just like that!
- That is incredible.

290
00:35:55,790 --> 00:35:58,320
- Hi, Mike, how you doin'?
- Hello, Jack.

291
00:35:59,080 --> 00:36:00,820
Hey, kids!

292
00:36:00,920 --> 00:36:05,130
Hi, George Monroe. That's a heck of
a handshake you got there, Ed.

293
00:36:05,210 --> 00:36:08,250
Harry! I saw you
on the golf course last week...

294
00:36:10,880 --> 00:36:14,470
Are you OK? Do you want something to eat?
Are you hungry?

295
00:36:16,010 --> 00:36:17,560
Do you want a cracker?

296
00:36:17,640 --> 00:36:20,100
- He's different.
- Completely different.

297
00:36:20,180 --> 00:36:22,010
No kidding.

298
00:36:22,100 --> 00:36:24,180
- He's so...
- Mysterious.

299
00:36:24,270 --> 00:36:25,650
Yeah.

300
00:36:25,730 --> 00:36:29,600
D'you imagine those hands are hot or cold?

301
00:36:29,690 --> 00:36:32,230
And just think what a single snip could do.

302
00:36:32,320 --> 00:36:33,520
Or undo.

303
00:36:36,240 --> 00:36:37,820
Eddie. Eddie.

304
00:36:37,910 --> 00:36:41,330
The guys and I want to invite you
to our card game Friday night.

305
00:36:41,410 --> 00:36:43,210
Would you like that?

306
00:36:43,290 --> 00:36:45,370
Only thing is... you can't cut!

307
00:36:58,510 --> 00:37:02,810
I have my own infirmity.
Never did me a bit of harm.

308
00:37:02,890 --> 00:37:07,020
Took some shrapnel during the war,
and ever since then I can't feel a thing!

309
00:37:09,030 --> 00:37:12,390
Don't you ever let anybody tell you
you have a handicap.

310
00:37:12,490 --> 00:37:15,690
Who's handicapped? My goodness.

311
00:37:16,490 --> 00:37:20,280
Don't be ridiculous!
You're not handicapped, you're...

312
00:37:20,370 --> 00:37:23,290
What do they call the... exceptional?

313
00:37:24,710 --> 00:37:29,870
My name's Joyce, and I noticed that you
have not tasted any of the ambrosia salad...

314
00:37:29,960 --> 00:37:32,340
...that I made especially for you.

315
00:37:33,170 --> 00:37:35,250
Allow me.

316
00:37:40,060 --> 00:37:41,170
Mmm!

317
00:37:41,270 --> 00:37:43,140
Mmmm!

318
00:37:43,230 --> 00:37:47,770
- You must try this. It's my mother's recipe.
- Doesn't this look gorgeous?

319
00:37:47,860 --> 00:37:52,400
With a green thumb like yours,
I sure could use your help at my place.

320
00:37:53,740 --> 00:37:55,480
I want a row of angels!

321
00:37:55,570 --> 00:38:01,110
I am so sorry, ladies, but he's promised to
come to my house first. Haven't you, Eddie?

322
00:38:01,200 --> 00:38:04,620
- I did?
- OK, everybody, grab your plates!

323
00:38:04,710 --> 00:38:06,500
Soup's on!

324
00:38:06,580 --> 00:38:08,540
Azhuzhizha zhigabab.

325
00:38:08,630 --> 00:38:10,790
- What?
- I thuzhizha zhizhgabab.

326
00:38:10,880 --> 00:38:13,370
It <i>is</i> shish kebab. It was a figure of speech.

327
00:38:13,460 --> 00:38:15,920
You shouldn't take things so literally.

328
00:38:19,220 --> 00:38:23,880
<i>"Let us pretend we are in the drawing</i>
<i>room and the hostess is serving tea."</i>

329
00:38:25,730 --> 00:38:28,850
"Many numerous little questions
confront us."

330
00:38:31,520 --> 00:38:34,860
"Should the man rise
when he accepts his cup of tea?"

331
00:38:36,700 --> 00:38:39,820
"May lump sugar be taken with the fingers?"

332
00:38:39,910 --> 00:38:41,150
No.

333
00:38:41,240 --> 00:38:44,080
"Is it good form to accept a second cup?"

334
00:38:45,290 --> 00:38:48,540
"Should the napkin be entirely unfolded...

335
00:38:48,630 --> 00:38:51,880
...or should the centre crease
be allowed to remain?"

336
00:38:51,960 --> 00:38:54,830
"It is so easy to commit
embarrassing blunders...

337
00:38:54,920 --> 00:38:58,540
...but etiquette tells us
just what is expected of us...

338
00:38:58,640 --> 00:39:02,500
...and guards us from all
humiliation and discomfort."

339
00:39:09,060 --> 00:39:11,140
Mm, yes. Boring.

340
00:39:12,190 --> 00:39:14,270
Let us switch to, uh...

341
00:39:15,240 --> 00:39:17,310
...to some poetry, hm?

342
00:39:21,780 --> 00:39:24,270
"There was an old man from the Cape,"

343
00:39:24,370 --> 00:39:26,910
"Who made himself garments of crepe."

344
00:39:27,000 --> 00:39:29,120
"When asked: Will they tear?"

345
00:39:29,210 --> 00:39:31,330
"He replied: Here and there,"

346
00:39:31,420 --> 00:39:33,910
"But they keep such a beautiful shape!"

347
00:39:36,130 --> 00:39:37,870
That's right.

348
00:39:37,970 --> 00:39:40,340
Go ahead, smile. It's funny.

349
00:39:40,430 --> 00:39:42,500
That's right.

350
00:40:04,330 --> 00:40:05,780
We're home.

351
00:40:05,870 --> 00:40:07,700
Shit.

352
00:40:07,790 --> 00:40:09,610
Everything's still sopping.

353
00:40:09,710 --> 00:40:13,210
- I can hardly wait to take a shower.
- And to sleep in a bed.

354
00:40:13,290 --> 00:40:16,160
If my parents have the alarm set,
I'm screwed.

355
00:40:16,250 --> 00:40:19,790
I told you to call them
and tell them we're coming back early.

356
00:40:19,880 --> 00:40:22,460
- But did you?
- Nope, he'd rather complain.

357
00:40:22,550 --> 00:40:24,710
How else am I supposed to get attention?

358
00:40:24,800 --> 00:40:28,850
- You didn't call your parents.
- They don't run things like a police state.

359
00:40:28,930 --> 00:40:31,560
- Bye. Thanks for driving, Denny.
- Bye.

360
00:40:31,640 --> 00:40:33,350
- Bye.
- Bye.

361
00:40:33,440 --> 00:40:35,560
- Don't forget your arm!
- Oh, yeah.

362
00:40:35,650 --> 00:40:37,720
Come on, Jim, let's go.

363
00:41:36,630 --> 00:41:40,490
There's somebody in my room!
Go look! Look!

364
00:41:40,590 --> 00:41:43,920
He's a murderer! He's got an axe!
He tried to kill me!

365
00:41:44,010 --> 00:41:46,300
- Everything's OK.
- Mom, go look!

366
00:41:46,390 --> 00:41:48,460
Go back to bed, Kevin.

367
00:41:53,350 --> 00:41:55,590
This way.

368
00:41:55,690 --> 00:42:00,270
Edward's come to live with us.
There is nothing to be upset about.

369
00:42:02,110 --> 00:42:04,900
OK. We'll have you set up here in a minute.

370
00:42:04,990 --> 00:42:08,320
We got a full queen-size bed here,
believe it or not.

371
00:42:09,910 --> 00:42:12,780
Oh, it's all made and everything. Good.

372
00:42:12,870 --> 00:42:14,580
There you go.

373
00:42:14,660 --> 00:42:16,700
What's the matter? What's wrong?

374
00:42:16,790 --> 00:42:18,870
She get you nervous?

375
00:42:19,710 --> 00:42:22,880
You've been cloistered away
up in that castle too long.

376
00:42:22,960 --> 00:42:28,010
You don't know about the wonderful world
of teenage girls. They're all crazy.

377
00:42:28,930 --> 00:42:32,590
- Here, this'll straighten you right out.
- What is it?

378
00:42:32,680 --> 00:42:34,760
Lemonade.

379
00:42:40,940 --> 00:42:42,730
I don't know what it is.

380
00:42:43,780 --> 00:42:45,850
They reach a certain age...

381
00:42:46,400 --> 00:42:50,190
They develop these gland things,
their bodies swell up...

382
00:42:50,950 --> 00:42:52,610
They go crazy.

383
00:42:55,750 --> 00:42:57,080
Glands?

384
00:42:58,170 --> 00:43:00,240
Yeah, glands.

385
00:43:00,880 --> 00:43:02,950
I try not to think about it.

386
00:43:20,810 --> 00:43:23,390
Good, isn't it?

387
00:43:23,940 --> 00:43:28,570
Now, you stay in Kevin's room tonight
and tomorrow we'll fix your room right up.

388
00:43:28,660 --> 00:43:30,480
Why did you have to bring him here?

389
00:43:30,570 --> 00:43:33,940
I couldn't have left him all alone.
You'd have done the same.

390
00:43:34,040 --> 00:43:35,910
Why does he have to stay <i>here?</i>

391
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:39,740
My goodness, Kim, I'm surprised at you.
He can't help the way he is.

392
00:43:39,830 --> 00:43:43,080
- Have a little sympathy.
- I do have sympathy.

393
00:43:43,170 --> 00:43:47,120
Then say a little greeting.
Come downstairs, shake the man's hand...

394
00:43:47,220 --> 00:43:49,970
- Shake his hand?!
- Well, not literally.

395
00:43:50,050 --> 00:43:54,180
- Goodness, you scared him half to death!
- I scared <i>him</i> to death?

396
00:43:59,270 --> 00:44:04,940
Hi, Bill! I just wanted you two
to have a proper introduction.

397
00:44:05,020 --> 00:44:07,180
Edward, this is our daughter Kim.

398
00:44:07,320 --> 00:44:10,730
Kim, this is Edward,
who's gonna live with us.

399
00:44:16,740 --> 00:44:17,990
Hi.

400
00:44:18,500 --> 00:44:20,990
H-h-h... H-h-h...

401
00:44:32,140 --> 00:44:33,930
Eddie!

402
00:44:34,010 --> 00:44:35,800
Thirsty?

403
00:44:39,230 --> 00:44:41,300
Kisses! Hush up!

404
00:44:43,230 --> 00:44:45,440
Shh, quiet now!

405
00:44:45,520 --> 00:44:51,190
Darlin', I can hardly hear myself think!
Momma's precious little baby girl...

406
00:44:54,240 --> 00:44:57,660
Aah! Wouldn't you like
a nice cool glass of lemonade?

407
00:44:59,200 --> 00:45:00,750
Lemonade?

408
00:45:10,340 --> 00:45:13,260
One chop to a guy's neck, and it's all over.

409
00:45:15,220 --> 00:45:18,640
Sharpest things in the world.
They can hack through anything.

410
00:45:19,520 --> 00:45:20,930
And...

411
00:45:39,040 --> 00:45:40,830
They give me the creeps.

412
00:45:40,910 --> 00:45:43,950
You should see the clown
in Miss Peters' yard.

413
00:45:44,670 --> 00:45:45,950
Kim!

414
00:45:47,000 --> 00:45:49,210
- Oh, no.
- That's him?

415
00:45:49,300 --> 00:45:51,500
- He's calling you, Kimba.
- Stop it!

416
00:45:51,590 --> 00:45:54,290
Edward, you forgot your cookies.

417
00:45:56,890 --> 00:45:59,380
Don't worry, Eddie. She's waiting for ya!

418
00:45:59,470 --> 00:46:01,880
- Stop!
- Let's go.

419
00:46:08,400 --> 00:46:10,850
Bill, Edward had lunch at Jackie's today...

420
00:46:10,940 --> 00:46:13,980
...and she just had
her kitchen completely redone.

421
00:46:14,070 --> 00:46:17,320
- I'll be darned.
- New paint, new cabinets, new floors...

422
00:46:17,410 --> 00:46:21,270
...a new microwave, new silent dishwasher...
- Isn't that wonderful?

423
00:46:21,370 --> 00:46:24,700
Jim, didn't you just tell me
your mom had her kitchen done too?

424
00:46:24,790 --> 00:46:27,360
Yeah, my dad bought himself
a bunch of new toys.

425
00:46:27,460 --> 00:46:30,960
Big-screen TV, CD players,
VCR with four heads...

426
00:46:31,050 --> 00:46:35,290
My goodness sake!
I wonder what it's like to be that rich.

427
00:46:36,050 --> 00:46:37,960
They keep things locked up.

428
00:46:38,050 --> 00:46:41,470
My father has his own room for his stuff
to make sure I can't use it.

429
00:46:41,560 --> 00:46:43,470
He won't even help me buy an old car.

430
00:46:43,560 --> 00:46:48,720
He probably wants you to pay for it yourself.
It builds character. You'll appreciate it more.

431
00:46:48,810 --> 00:46:50,270
Dad!

432
00:46:50,360 --> 00:46:55,180
Speaking of money... I understand you're
not charging for your gardening, Edward.

433
00:46:55,280 --> 00:46:58,230
Now, Bill... Marge made him cookies today.

434
00:46:58,320 --> 00:47:00,400
Sweetheart...

435
00:47:01,280 --> 00:47:04,620
You can't buy
the necessities of life with cookies.

436
00:47:05,620 --> 00:47:08,460
You can't buy a car with cookies.
Am I right, Jim?

437
00:47:08,540 --> 00:47:10,660
Uh, that's true, sir, you can't.

438
00:47:12,170 --> 00:47:15,120
I... I can't eat that. He used his hands.

439
00:47:15,220 --> 00:47:17,620
It's... I don't think it's sanitary.

440
00:47:22,430 --> 00:47:24,840
I'm sorry.

441
00:47:28,020 --> 00:47:30,890
Honey, you want me
to help you clean that up?

442
00:47:30,980 --> 00:47:32,890
No, that's OK.

443
00:47:33,610 --> 00:47:35,730
I'll be right back.

444
00:48:22,280 --> 00:48:27,280
Alexis? Oh, this can't possibly be my Alexis!

445
00:48:27,950 --> 00:48:32,120
She looks so beautiful! Look at you! Sweetie!

446
00:48:32,920 --> 00:48:34,990
She's gorgeous. Thank you!

447
00:48:36,880 --> 00:48:39,960
It won't be long.
She just has to decide on the style.

448
00:48:40,050 --> 00:48:42,130
And then it'll be fine.

449
00:48:53,480 --> 00:48:57,690
I was hopin' for somethin' big
and kinda bouffant. Kinda like mine?

450
00:48:57,780 --> 00:49:02,690
Now don't you worry, Kisses, you're gonna
be just fine. You're gonna be so pretty.

451
00:49:02,780 --> 00:49:04,490
Yes, you are. Oh!

452
00:49:04,570 --> 00:49:06,450
Oh! My!

453
00:49:07,910 --> 00:49:09,990
Oh! Ohh!

454
00:49:20,920 --> 00:49:24,090
Oh! Eddie, is there anything you can't do?

455
00:49:24,180 --> 00:49:28,180
You take my very breath away, I swear.
Look at this!

456
00:49:29,770 --> 00:49:31,640
Have you ever cut a woman's hair?

457
00:49:31,730 --> 00:49:33,520
Would you cut mine?

458
00:50:41,380 --> 00:50:45,510
That was the single most thrillin' experience
of my whole life.

459
00:51:50,490 --> 00:51:52,820
They're getting the head of the company!

460
00:51:52,910 --> 00:51:56,160
- I'm home!
- Hi, honey. We're in here.

461
00:51:56,250 --> 00:51:58,160
- Hi.
- Hi!

462
00:51:58,250 --> 00:52:00,040
What did you do to your hair?

463
00:52:00,120 --> 00:52:02,200
Edward cut it. Isn't it wild?

464
00:52:03,840 --> 00:52:07,040
Hello? Oh, I can't believe
I'm talking to you in person.

465
00:52:07,130 --> 00:52:09,210
This is such an honour.

466
00:52:10,720 --> 00:52:13,210
Yes. He's right here.

467
00:52:13,300 --> 00:52:15,300
So then you know all about it.

468
00:52:15,390 --> 00:52:18,720
Uh-huh. Well, that's exactly
what I've been using.

469
00:52:20,020 --> 00:52:25,770
Well, I've had a little trouble getting it
the right consistency... well, just a little.

470
00:52:26,730 --> 00:52:28,810
I'll try that. Uh-huh.

471
00:52:31,030 --> 00:52:33,820
Well, what imaginative suggestions.

472
00:52:35,290 --> 00:52:38,780
I sure will. Thank you so much. Bye-bye.

473
00:52:39,870 --> 00:52:42,110
No wonder she's the head of the company.

474
00:52:42,210 --> 00:52:45,830
You know, she started out as
a sales representative just like me.

475
00:52:45,920 --> 00:52:49,700
I've always wanted to talk to her,
but until now I never had a reason.

476
00:52:49,800 --> 00:52:51,880
Thanks, Edward.

477
00:52:52,800 --> 00:52:55,210
- She had some ideas?
- You bet she did.

478
00:52:56,640 --> 00:52:59,560
- Uh-huh!
- Mm-hm!

479
00:53:09,650 --> 00:53:11,730
I'll get that.

480
00:53:53,070 --> 00:53:55,360
Edward. We're here.

481
00:53:55,450 --> 00:53:57,770
Come on, let's get you sharpened up.

482
00:54:01,160 --> 00:54:03,780
- You got it?
- No. I can't believe this.

483
00:54:03,870 --> 00:54:05,750
This is such a drag.

484
00:54:06,880 --> 00:54:08,340
Hi!

485
00:54:11,800 --> 00:54:13,870
- Bye.
- Bye.

486
00:54:15,220 --> 00:54:16,930
Do you have a key?

487
00:54:17,010 --> 00:54:18,210
No.

488
00:54:18,300 --> 00:54:22,520
- I could have sworn they were in my purse.
- Well, we're stranded.

489
00:54:26,810 --> 00:54:28,890
